  "text": "Antigen-independent, but cytokine-and STAT4-dependent, IFN-␥ expression by LCMV-immune CD8 T cells following primary MCMV infection. To dissect the T cell IFN-␥ response in the absence of antigen, LCMV-immune CD8 T cell responses were evaluated during infection with unrelated MCMV (Fig. 7A) . Cells for study were harvested from uninfected mice, LCMV-immune mice without a viral challenge, and LCMV-immune mice infected with MCMV for 16 h, 1.5 days, and 3.5 days. The LCMV-specific (LCMV-Tet ϩ ) but not the nonspecific (LCMV-Tet Ϫ ) CD8 T cells were induced to express both pSTAT4 and IFN-␥ during acute primary MCMV infection ( Fig. 7B and C) . Their proportions (Fig. 7C) and yields ( Fig. 7D ) peaked at times corresponding to the systemic innate cytokine response, i.e., day 1.5 (see Fig. 6 ). Despite the increasing number of LCMV-Tet ϩ CD8 T cells expressing IFN-␥, there was no overall expansion of the LCMV-specific CD8 T cells during MCMV infection (Fig. 7D ). This was in contrast to that following an LCMV challenge (kinetics, Fig. 4D ) and in a control day 3.5 arm of LCMV infection for these experiments (Fig. 7D) . Thus, at times of innate cytokine expression, the LCMV-specific CD8 T cells in immune mice were capable of responding to an unrelated viral infection with pSTAT4 activation and IFN-␥ expression but were not induced to expand. The responding T cells were further characterized as central (Tcm) or effector (Tem) memory cells on the basis of their levels of CD11a, CD127, and CD62L expression [CITATION_1] . The CD8 T cells examined were LCMV-Tet ϩ compared to LCMV-Tet Ϫ cells from LCMV-immune uninfected or day 1.5 MCMV-infected mice and LCMV-Tet ϩ CD8 T cells expressing IFN-␥ from day 1.5 MCMVinfected mice ( Fig. 7E and F) . The majority, approximately 70%, of the LCMV-immune CD8 T cells were Tem cells, i.e., CD11a high, CD127 ϩ , and CD62L low, but approximately 30% were Tcm, i.e., CD11a high, CD127 ϩ , and CD62L high, and the LCMVspecific cells expressing IFN-␥ were proportionally distributed in these two subsets. KLRG1 expression was used to identify effector and memory cells. Most of the immune T cells, as well as the immune cells expressing IFN-␥ during MCMV infection, were negative for KLRG1. Interestingly, the frequencies of KLRG1-positive cells increased during infection such that approximately 20 to 40% of the IFN-␥-expressing cells had the marker under these conditions. Similar results were obtained when pSTAT4 induction during infection was analyzed (not shown). Thus, the LCMV-specific CD8 T cells responding to MCMV infection in the LCMV-immune mice were Tem cells but small proportions were in other cell subsets.",
